page.title: 12BRAFFORD'S WOODS.
page.content: The farmer owns a large wood of thirty seven acres. This wood is split into two. This is where a lot of wildlife lives. They have partridges and pheasants which are fed on a nutritious grain and a compound with protein in it. In the wood the pheasants are kept in a run. When the pheasants are fed crows and robins come and feed on the grain as well. Rabbits have become immune to disease. There used to be very few rabbits because of myxomotosis but it does not bother them as much as it used to do. They also have foxes but these are not as much trouble as the rabbits. The Wold's Way also goes through the wood.
